<p id="d1e1977">The logistic function is a well-known example of an epidemiological sigmoid curve (
 <xref rid="b38" ref-type="bibr">Van Mieghem, 2016</xref>, 
 <xref rid="b39" ref-type="bibr">Verhulst, 1845</xref>). We assume the cumulative number of infected cases 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e1985" display="inline" altimg="si138.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>y</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> in region 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2003" display="inline" altimg="si137.svg">
   <mi>i</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> at time 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2009" display="inline" altimg="si140.svg">
   <mi>k</mi>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> to follow a logistic function: 
 <disp-formula id="fd5">
  <label>(5)</label>
  <math id="d1e2020" display="block" altimg="si65.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>y</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>[</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mo>]</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo>
    <mfrac>
     <mrow>
      <msub>
       <mrow>
        <mi>y</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mi>∞</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mi>i</mi>
       </mrow>
      </msub>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mn>1</mn>
      <mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mo>
      <msup>
       <mrow>
        <mi>e</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mo>
        <msub>
         <mrow>
          <mi>K</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mi>i</mi>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mrow>
         <mo>(</mo>
         <mi>k</mi>
         <mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mo>
         <msub>
          <mrow>
           <mi>t</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow>
           <mn>0</mn>
           <mo>,</mo>
           <mi>i</mi>
          </mrow>
         </msub>
         <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
       </mrow>
      </msup>
     </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <mo>,</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2094" display="inline" altimg="si66.svg">
   <msub>
    <mrow>
     <mi>y</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>∞</mi>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the long-term fraction of infections, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2108" display="inline" altimg="si67.svg">
   <msub>
    <mrow>
     <mi>K</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the logistic growth rate and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2119" display="inline" altimg="si68.svg">
   <msub>
    <mrow>
     <mi>t</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mn>0</mn>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the inflection point, also known as the epidemic peak. The parameters 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2133" display="inline" altimg="si66.svg">
   <msub>
    <mrow>
     <mi>y</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>∞</mi>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2147" display="inline" altimg="si67.svg">
   <msub>
    <mrow>
     <mi>K</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="d1e2157" display="inline" altimg="si68.svg">
   <msub>
    <mrow>
     <mi>t</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mn>0</mn>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> are estimated for each region separately using a nonlinear curve fitting procedure, which is explained in Appendix F. Other sigmoid curves, like the Hill function and Gompertz function, are also discussed in Appendix F.
</p>
